{"slug":"intro-chains","graph":"both","title":"Three hops to anyone","sub":"the three cheapest intro routes to each prospect, major lab, and funder","headline":"Anthropic, OpenAI, and Google DeepMind sit <strong>two hops</strong> from AoC — but every one of the 24 company routes opens through a rival, and Gray Swan AI alone fronts 14 of them.","prose":{"intro":"<p>The map shows who is adjacent to whom; this panel turns that into asks. For eight company targets — the top prospects, the major labs, and one VC — plus the top five funders, we compute the three cheapest intro routes each, then count who keeps showing up in the middle. The recurring middlemen are the relationships worth investing in.</p>","how":"<p>The route-finder works like a maps app asked for alternates: the best path, then the next-best that differs somewhere, never revisiting a stop. Each hop has a price. A business tie costs 1, a shared investor 2, a rival 10 — so a route through one competitor wins only if it saves ten partner hops. Three routes per target means two backups when a relationship goes cold. On the funding side, routes start from the 3 grantees nearest AoC (Gray Swan AI, Haize Labs, Irregular), and every hop counts the same. One structural fact: every person in the funding graph has exactly one edge, so no route passes <em>through</em> a person — a chain can only end at one. That is why the person routes end with a name and a role.</p>","method":"<p>Yen (1971) k-shortest loopless paths, k=3, via networkx <code>shortest_simple_paths</code> (Dijkstra subroutine on the weighted company graph; unweighted BFS hops on the funding graph). Edge weights business=1, shared-investor=2, competitor=10 are design choices, not measurements — reweighting reorders routes but cannot create reachability. For the 7 company pairs with two edge types we keep the cheaper. Targets were curated at bake time from the competitor-nominations and funder-shortlist panels plus the four majors; all 8 company targets sit inside AoC's 171-node component (0 unreachable), while 1 of 5 shortlist funders (Insight Partners) have no funding-graph path from any AoC-linked grantee. Funding caveats: 85/199 edges lack a year, and affiliation edges carry roles but no dollars.</p>"},"caveat":"Every company route starts through a rival, and it has to: 4 of AoC's 5 edges are competitor ties, and the fifth — an unverified business tie to AIUC — is a dead end, since AIUC's only edge points back to AoC. Remove the rival edges and AoC is cut off from the market entirely. These routes exist because rivals see us, not because partners do yet.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":492},"funding":{"nodes":200,"edges":199}},"data":{"companyChains":[{"target":{"id":"uipath","label":"UiPath","graph":"companies"},"why":"top nominated prospect","chains":[{"score":13,"nodes":[{"id":"agents-of-chaos","label":"Agents of Chaos","graph":"companies"},{"id":"gray-swan-ai","label":"Gray Swan AI","graph":"companies"},{"id":"openai","label":"OpenAI","graph":"companies"},{"id":"microsoft","label":"Microsoft","graph":"companies"},{"id":"uipath","label":"UiPath","graph":"companies"}],"edges":[{"label":"competitor","verified":true},{"label":"business","verified":true},{"label":"business","verified":true},{"label":"business","verified":true}]},{"score":13,"nodes":[{"id":"agents-of-chaos","label":"Agents of Chaos","graph":"companies"},{"id":"haize-labs","label":"Haize Labs","graph":"companies"},{"id":"anthropic","label":"Anthropic","graph":"companies"},{"id":"microsoft","label":"Microsoft","graph":"companies"},{"id":"uipath","label":"UiPath","graph":"companies"}],"edges":[{"label":"competitor","verified":false},{"label":"business","verified":true},{"label":"business","verified":true},{"label":"business","verified":true}]},{"score":13,"nodes":[{"id":"agents-of-chaos","label":"Agents of Chaos","graph":"companies"},{"id":"gray-swan-ai","label":"Gray Swan AI","graph":"companies"},{"id":"anthropic","label":"Anthropic","